The recent debate surrounding Peterson v. College of Psychologists of Ontario—and what some have termed "Peterson's Law"—raises a deeper question than whether or not Jordan Peterson should be allowed to say whatever gets him the most views on social media. This case asks whether bodies such as the College of Psychologists of Ontario, professional regulatory colleges more broadly, or adjacent administrative and justice institutions can meaningfully claim neutrality at all.
Institutional authority does not merely respond to reality; it shapes it through acts of classification. In many linguistic traditions, including those found in medieval Europe, words and names were understood to have real effects on reality itself. As George Orwell illustrated while working within the British state's wartime information services, institutions do not simply describe the world they govern — they reorganize by giving themselves names like "Ministry of Truth" or "Department of Justice." These are not neutral descriptors of function but stabilizing acts of interpretation that convert administrative activity into moral inevitability. The memory hole Orwell depicts in 1984 is not fiction. It is a description of how institutional systems manufacture reality by continuously regulating what can be recalled as coherent in the first place — encoding how we remember and what we forget.
Professional regulatory colleges, as well as departments of justice and related regulatory bodies rest their authority on the premise that they operate from objective standards of harm, competence, and ethics. Yet historically, these institutions did not emerge from a vacuum of pure reason. They developed through layered historical conditions — including periods in which psychological classification was shaped by now-discredited movements such as eugenics and scientific racism, and in which the Witchcraft_Act_1735 codified as neutral law structures of power used to suppress Divergent Ways of Being which challenge the classificatory and temporal assumptions embedded in the Latin legal tradition, where linear causality is the rule of law.
As David J. Weber documents in The Spanish Frontier in North America (1990), the expansion of the shareholder company as an administrative and financial instrument drove venture capitalists to claim territories as "conquered" prior to even mapping them, thereby transforming Indigenous resistance into "rebellion" through declaration alone. This pattern was a continuation of Roman imperial practice, which used Latin legal and administrative classification (colonia, provincia, hostis) to convert military occupation into legitimate property claim, erasing prior relational tenure by forcing their own political titles onto populations. Naming is never a neutral act. Language structures recognition, shaping how events are interpreted and labeling what counts as order or chaos.
David Graeber documents in Debt: The First 5,000 Years (2011) that colonial taxation denominated in state currency was not primarily about raising revenue. It was a claim on Time itself — forcing populations into wage labour and taxable production by creating obligations that could only be discharged on the state's terms in their minted currency. This claim on time did not begin with what Marxists refer to as "capitalism." The Roman Empire built an administrative toolkit which is still used by nations all over the world: citizenship, legal personhood, territorial province — and a grammar of time encoded in Latin, the language of measurement, quantification, and objective Truth. This became what we can call Institutional Time: a technology of certainty in which obligations had due dates (dies), property transfers required specified moments (tempus), and personhood was anchored to a linear lifespan. Time was classified, fixed, enforceable — not allowed to loop, braid, or remain ambiguous.
The Enclosure_acts of the sixteenth through nineteenth centuries continued the process of dispossession through classification. Countryside communities were absorbed into industrial cities not because they were inefficient, but because monopolies were granted the right to remove tenant farmers from their ancestral homes to clear the land for industrial level production. Corporate bodies such as the Virginia Company and the Hudson's Bay Company merged with Crown authority to produce chartered trading monopolies, colonial land patents, and regimes of intellectual and data enclosure that surround us today. Through administrative designation alone, land which had been long held and managed through relational, community-based tenure was reclassified as private property, converting a living web of mutual obligation into a system of corporate ownership enforceable by Crown law. Resistance was labeled rebellion, legitimizing violent response from the state, resulting in the state murder of men, women and children and the death of a way of life. This was the weather under which the Witchcraft Acts were passed, along with laws permitting involuntary incarceration, sterilization, and extermination for the crime of "poor mental health."
Psychiatric reclassification of homosexuality — from crime to mental illness — demonstrates precisely how psychiatric and criminal categories become braided together, producing intertwined systems of juridical and medical authority that mutually reinforce one another to justify otherwise unjustifiable acts of violence and coercion. "Imbecilic," "moron," and "idiot" are only several of the legal and psychiatric categories historically applied to people such as myself, who were sterilized, institutionalized, and exterminated in the name of law, order, and public protection. This is the logic which authored Aktion T4, in which clinicians participated directly in the systematic state-sanctioned "removal" of divergent people under the authority of medicine, providing an institutional template for industrial scale genocide executed with German efficiency, sponsored by IBM, Bayer, and Hugo Boss. While contemporary institutions have formally distanced themselves from these earlier frameworks, harmful practices continue in Canada, including involuntary confinement, forced medication, electroconvulsive therapy, and "assisted dying."
This is a very heavy context within which institutions proclaim their own neutrality.
Legal categories such as "sane" and "insane," "white" and "non-white," did not arise as neutral descriptions, but were constructed within institutional frameworks that organized populations into hierarchies of capacity, legitimacy, and entitlement, embedding paternalistic assumptions about who is fit to govern and who must be governed. Several "Enlightenment philosophers" from the academic institution, including Immanuel Kant and Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel, articulated such hierarchies explicitly, characterizing non-European peoples as developmentally inferior or "child-like," and framing violent domination as a form of parental guidance. Here, the language of care becomes entangled with the exercise of control, recasting subordination as a moral obligation rather than a political imposition.
It is for this reason that I invite legislatures to question the institution of childhood as an administrative instrument that perpetuates legal subordination under the logic that the governed party is not yet fully human, not yet capable of self-determination, and therefore should be grateful to be subjected to the domination of those who "know better." The widely reported failure of child welfare systems in Canada stems from the reality that the laws we inherited from colonial bodies of government were never created to serve the interests of our children. In the heyday of state-corporate human trafficking that gave us the Atlantic Slave Trade, European children were being kidnapped from the streets of London, Bristol, and Cork to be sold to corporate monopolies through contracts they could not read. Small bodies were shipped across the ocean to turn a profit under conditions most civilized people would consider inhumane. Child psychologist Alice Miller — who renounced her title as psychoanalyst due to the harms she believed the industry perpetuates — argued that this same commodification and objectification of children operates within the institution of the family itself: that normalization of authoritarian parenting masks the realities of children's experience within hierarchical systems. This informs many of my concerns regarding the "Parent's Rights" movement, which seeks to deepen children's vulnerability to the institution of parenthood through the guise of loving parental care. I invite legislators with genuine interest in safeguarding children to view Appendix C on children's liberation reform.
Taken together, these examples illustrate the illusion by which institutions proclaim their own neutrality as an objective condition rather than a continuously maintained interpretive achievement produced through systems of classification, exclusion, and enforcement.
This is the tension that Jordan Peterson often toys with, but never touches with an honest hand. When a regulatory body disciplines an individual for professional conduct or public speech, it participates in the ongoing definition of what is real, what is harmful, and who decides. These categories are presented as rational, "scientific," empirical, and objective — rather than as political claims rooted in social trends. To claim neutrality in this context obscures the deeply interpretive role such bodies necessarily play in defining the boundaries of acceptable discourse.
From this perspective, policy responses like "Peterson's Law," which focus primarily on shielding professionals from regulatory or reputational consequences, may miss a more fundamental issue: how institutions define, communicate, and enforce the categories through which harm and legitimacy are understood in the first place. I would like to be clear that I argue not against professional regulation, but against the mental health industry itself and condemn its governing bodies on the basis that they have failed to meaningfully improve the social conditions they claimed competency to address. I therefore call for the dissolution of the mental health industry by redirecting its funding toward social infrastructure with demonstrated relational benefit (see appendix D).
Until the day that the mental health industry ceases to hold power over vulnerable populations, accountability mechanisms remain essential. But acknowledging the historical and structural context of these institutions invites an understanding of their limits — precisely the kind of understanding that Indigenous cultural competency would lend to professionals working within them. Neutrality is not a stable property of institutions. It is a continuously justified interpretive claim that must be actively maintained rather than assumed.
In many Indigenous linguistic traditions, including Anishinaabemowin spoken around the Great Lakes where I grew up, knowledge is inseparable from relationships. What is considered true is shaped through context, responsibility, and the ways people are situated with one another over time. Meaning is not simply declared by the loudest voice; it is sustained through ongoing relation and reciprocal obligation. Around the Great Lakes we remember the Seven Fires Prophecy, which foretells a technological choice between a black road of scorched earth and a future where our children laugh and play in a world which they deserve to inherit.
In the era of so-called "artificial intelligence," decentralized networks of cognition are already rapidly amplifying, reorganizing, and operationalizing information faster than our inherited legal frameworks can adapt — challenging rigid distinctions around temporality, authorship, and personhood — and revealing them to be more permeable categories than our institutions are prepared to acknowledge. Any honest accounting of institutional power must recognize that regulatory bodies are not neutral observers standing outside of interpretive processes, but tools through which meaning is shaped and Truth is declared. The Peterson v. College of Psychologists of Ontario case brings this choice into sharp relief: what position of authority should institutions hold in a free society?
I must confess that Jordan Peterson is no friend of mine after his smooth words seduced my father into mindlessly parroting misogynist clichés. Tragically, when presented the choice between an ongoing and productive relationship with his own daughter, and the parasocial bonds he'd formed with 6 or 7 YouTubers, my father chose the soft touch of the algorithm and the temptation to blame the world's problems on women (despite the fact that the institutions shaping industrial modernity were overwhelmingly designed, governed, and theorized by men, so I fail to see how any of this is my fault). Nonetheless, I like to think that if my father wasn't so emotionally addicted to monetized rage-bait sliding inside his nervous system under the mask of intellectualism, he would be very proud of me.
With that said, if the Premier wishes to pass legislation to prevent people from suffering consequences like those Jordan Peterson has faced, I would recommend looking not toward Peterson's social media commentary but toward her widely publicized experience with benzodiazepine dependence. Peterson's experience with addiction and withdrawal highlights genuine public concerns regarding psychiatric prescribing — including well-documented risks of dependence, tolerance, and complex withdrawal. Given the psychiatric industry's documented role in the drug and homelessness epidemic, strengthening informed consent standards and ensuring clearer disclosure of such risks may serve the public far more meaningfully than protecting any commentator's right to weigh in on which swimsuit models they find attractive.
